# TLS via DuckDNS: a free subdomain (ours: see deploy/README.md) pointed at the
# static IP. Telegram requires valid HTTPS for webhooks; Let's Encrypt issues the
# cert through the plain HTTP-01 challenge on port 80 — no DNS plugin and no
# DuckDNS token ever touches the VM. Because the IP is STATIC, DuckDNS is set
# once; the updater cron that dynamic-IP tutorials add is unnecessary here.
#
# Why DuckDNS over sslip.io: duckdns.org is on the Public Suffix List, so every
# subdomain gets its OWN Let's Encrypt rate-limit bucket. sslip.io is one shared
# domain that routinely exhausts LE limits and stalls issuance.
{$N8N_DOMAIN} {
    reverse_proxy n8n:5678
}
